    <text>
        <body><div type="bibliography">
                
                <p>Never published before this edition.</p>
            </div><div type="edition" xml:lang="grc" xml:space="preserve">
                
                <ab>
                    <lb n="0"/><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="line"/><certainty locus="name" match=".."/>
                    <lb n="1"/><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/><orig><unclear>λκ</unclear></orig><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/>
                    <lb n="2"/><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/> <w lemma="δεκάτα"><supplied reason="lost">δ</supplied>εκά<supplied reason="lost">ταν</supplied></w> <gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/><certainty locus="name" match=".."/>
                    <lb n="2a"/><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="line"/><certainty locus="name" match=".."/>
                </ab>
            </div><div type="apparatus" xml:space="preserve">
            
                <p/>
               </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="fr">
            <p><supplied reason="lost">Un tel</supplied> <supplied reason="subaudible">a consacré</supplied> au titre de la dîme <gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/>.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="en">
            <p><supplied reason="lost">So and so</supplied> <supplied reason="subaudible">dedicated</supplied> as a tithe <gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/>.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="it">
            <p><supplied reason="lost">Il tale</supplied> <supplied reason="subaudible">ha dedicato</supplied> come decima <gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/>.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="ar">
            <p/>
         </div><div type="commentary">
                
             <p>The word 'tithe' is restored on behalf of the very numerous other instances of such dedications. In fact, it would also be possible to read the name of the 
             goddess Hekata, but inscriptions on marble for this deity are very few and this reading seems less plausible.</p>
             <p>The name of the dedicant should have stood above. The two letters partially preserved at line 1, although incomplete, are read with certainty. A tempting restoration would thus produce one of the names with <foreign xml:lang="grc">Ἀλκι-</foreign> already known 
             in Cyrenaica.</p>
            </div></body>
    </text>
